[{"id":"VR252390","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">This question is a long free-response question. Show your work for each part of the question. (15 points, suggested time 25 minutes)</p>\n\n<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a block, which has a mass of M, being pulled along a horizontal floor by a rope that is positioned at an angle of theta to the horizontal.\" height=\"111\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR252390.g01.png\" width=\"225\" /></div>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">A block of mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"M\"><math alttext=\"M\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> is pulled by a rope that makes an angle <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta\"><math alttext=\"theta\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> (theta) above the horizontal, as shown above. The coefficient of kinetic friction between the block and floor is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"mu\"><math alttext=\"mu\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> (mu).</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"item_part part_id:A part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"A\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The block is initially at rest and starts accelerating to the right along the floor. Three students each draw a diagram to indicate all of the forces that are exerted on the block as it moves. In the students’ diagrams, which are shown below, the lengths of the arrows indicate the relative magnitudes of the forces.</p>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows three force diagrams, labeled Student 1 through Student 3‘s diagram, each with four forces extending from a common point. The diagrams include equally spaced gridlines. The arrangement of Student 1‘s diagram is as follows: an arrow labeled Friction extends horizontally to the left by one gridline, an arrow labeled Normal extends vertically upwards two gridlines, an arrow labeled Rope extends diagonally upwards two gridlines and to the right two gridlines, and an arrow labeled Weight extends vertically downwards by four gridlines. The arrangement of Student 2‘s diagram is as follows: an arrow labeled Friction extends horizontally to the left by two gridlines, an arrow labeled Normal extends vertically upwards two gridlines, an arrow labeled Rope extends diagonally upwards two gridlines and to the right two gridlines, and an arrow labeled Weight extends vertically downwards by four gridlines. The arrangement of Student 3‘s diagram is as follows: an arrow labeled Friction extends horizontally to the left by two gridlines, an arrow labeled Normal extends vertically upwards two gridlines, an arrow labeled Rope extends diagonally upwards one gridline and to the right two gridlines, and an arrow labeled Weight extends vertically downwards by four gridlines.\" height=\"229\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR252390.g02.png\" width=\"565\" /></div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Only one of the students has drawn a diagram that could correctly represent the forces. The other two students’ diagrams are incorrect.</p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a) Which student has drawn a diagram that could correctly represent the forces exerted on the block?</p>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252390_rubric"},{"id":"VR252390","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:B part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"B\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b) For the incorrect student diagrams, explain why the diagram could not represent the forces exerted on the block. If there is more than one specific reason a diagram is incorrect, identify each of the reasons.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252390_rubric"},{"id":"VR252390","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:C part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"C\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(c) Briefly explain why slightly increasing the angle <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta\"><math alttext=\"theta\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> (without changing the magnitude of the force exerted by the rope) <span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">could</span> cause a <span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">decrease</span> in the block’s acceleration.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252390_rubric"},{"id":"VR252390","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:D part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"D\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Suppose the rope is pulled with a force that has a magnitude that is one-third the weight of the block, or <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"the fraction M g over 3\"><math alttext=\"the fraction M g over 3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi>M</mi><mi>g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. In this case, when the block accelerates, its acceleration is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"a equals g times, open parenthesis, one third of cosine theta, plus, the fraction mu over 3 times the sine of theta, minus mu, close parenthesis\"><math alttext=\"a equals g times, open parenthesis, one third of cosine theta, plus, the fraction mu over 3 times the sine of theta, minus mu, close parenthesis\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>g</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi>cos</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi>sin</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>−</mo><mi>μ</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(d) Explain why the above equation is consistent with the claim that an increase in the angle <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta\"><math alttext=\"theta\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> <span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">could</span> cause a <span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">decrease</span> in the acceleration.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252390_rubric"},{"id":"VR252390","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:E part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"E\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a block, which has a mass of M, on a horizontal floor with a vertical rope attached to the top of the block. Coordinate axes are shown indicating that the positive x direction is to the right and the positive y direction is upward.\" height=\"146\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR252390.g03.png\" width=\"275\" /></div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The rope is now attached to the center of the top of the block, as shown above. The force exerted by the rope is initially zero newtons at time <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t equals 0\"><math alttext=\"t equals 0\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. The force steadily increases, becomes equal to the block’s weight <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"W\"><math alttext=\"W\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>W</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> at time <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t sub 1\"><math alttext=\"t sub 1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, and continues to increase further. Three students sketch the graphs shown below to represent the normal force exerted by the floor on the block as a function of time <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t\"><math alttext=\"t\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. One of the graphs is consistent with this scenario, while the other graphs are not consistent with this scenario.</p>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows three graphs, labeled Graph 1 through Graph 3, each in the first quadrant of the coordinate plane with the origin labeled O. The horizontal axes are each labeled t, and a point labeled t sub 1 is located three quarters of the way across the axis. The vertical axes are each labeled Normal Force, and a point labeled W is located three quarters of the way up the axis. The data represented in each graph are as follows. The line in Graph 1 begins at the point labeled W on the vertical axis above the origin and moves diagonally downwards and to the right, ending at the point labeled t sub 1 on the horizontal axis. Graph 2 contains two line segments, the first of which begins at the point labeled W on the vertical axis above the origin and moves horizontally to the right, ending directly above the point labeled t sub 1 on the horizontal axis. The second line segment begins directly on the horizontal axis at the point labeled t sub 1, aligned with the origin, and moves horizontally to the right until ending at the rightmost point along the horizontal axis. A vertical dotted line connects the end of the first line segment to the beginning of the second line segment. The line in Graph 3 begins at the origin and moves diagonally upwards and to the right until reaching a point directly above the point labeled t sub 1 on the horizontal axis, and at a height aligned with the point labeled W on the vertical axis. It then moves horizontally to the right until ending at the rightmost point along the horizontal axis.\" height=\"149\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR252390.g04.png\" width=\"476\" /></div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(e) Which graph is consistent with the scenario in which the force exerted by the rope on the block steadily increases?</p>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252390_rubric"},{"id":"VR252390","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:F part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"F\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(f) Identify all features of the other two graphs that make them inconsistent with this scenario. Explain your reasoning.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252390_rubric"},{"id":"VR252390","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:G part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"G\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a diagram showing two identical blocks with mass M hanging from vertical ropes that are attached to a ceiling. The left rope has length L and the right rope has length L over 2. A dashed line that is part of a circular arc is centered on each block, with the block at the location of the lowest point in the circular arc.\" height=\"261\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR252390.g05.png\" width=\"400\" /></div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">With one end of the rope still attached to the block, the other end of the rope is attached to a ceiling to create a pendulum with length <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"L\"><math alttext=\"L\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, where <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"L\"><math alttext=\"L\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> is much greater than the dimensions of the block. A second pendulum is made from an identical block and a rope of length <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"L divided by 2\"><math alttext=\"L divided by 2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, as shown above. Both pendulums are displaced by the same small angle and released from rest.</p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(g) Does the longer pendulum or the shorter pendulum have a greater period of oscillation? Briefly explain your choice without reference to equations, but by describing the restoring forces exerted on and motion of each block.</p>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252390_rubric"}]